00:40:20.550 --> 00:40:22.780
of advancement in companies.

00:40:22.780 --> 00:40:24.950
And it's my take.

00:40:24.950 --> 00:40:28.050
I mean, there are other
books with other takes on it,

00:40:28.050 --> 00:40:31.970
but this was my experience and
validated by the CEO interviews

00:40:31.970 --> 00:40:32.900
I did.

00:40:32.900 --> 00:40:37.610
So I guess it's the
difference between a focus

00:40:37.610 --> 00:40:40.520
on self-defeating.

00:40:40.520 --> 00:40:44.490
That's not all she
does, and we should.

00:40:44.490 --> 00:40:45.660
I mean, that's important.

00:40:45.660 --> 00:40:48.165
But also an offensive strategy.

00:40:48.165 --> 00:40:49.415
AUDIENCE: Thank you very much.

00:40:49.415 --> 00:40:50.665
SUSAN PACKARD: You're welcome.

00:40:54.880 --> 00:40:55.590
Yes, Jeremy?

00:40:58.540 --> 00:41:01.170
JEREMY STERN: So you've been
on this whirlwind book tour

00:41:01.170 --> 00:41:03.060
now since February?

00:41:03.060 --> 00:41:04.090
SUSAN PACKARD: Mhm.

00:41:04.090 --> 00:41:08.290
JEREMY STERN: Been all over the
country to some amazing places.

00:41:08.290 --> 00:41:09.972
What's resonated?

00:41:09.972 --> 00:41:12.180
What have you found has
resonated with your audiences

00:41:12.180 --> 00:41:13.763
about the book and
about your message?

00:41:17.689 --> 00:41:19.730
SUSAN PACKARD: While I've
spoken to mixed groups,

00:41:19.730 --> 00:41:23.190
the majority of the groups
I've spoken to are all women.

00:41:23.190 --> 00:41:26.150
And when all women
are together, there's

00:41:26.150 --> 00:41:28.480
a real let down your
hair kind of thing.

00:41:33.610 --> 00:41:35.670
In the book on the
chapter on grit,

00:41:35.670 --> 00:41:38.850
for example, I talk about
some very difficult situations

00:41:38.850 --> 00:41:40.160
I had in my 20s.

00:41:40.160 --> 00:41:42.690
One was being
assaulted in a hotel.

00:41:42.690 --> 00:41:46.340
These kinds of things
that getting together

00:41:46.340 --> 00:41:49.840
and to talk about those things
from a practical standpoint?

00:41:49.840 --> 00:41:52.550
I mean, who teaches you
how to travel on the job?

00:41:52.550 --> 00:41:54.210
Nobody taught me.

00:41:54.210 --> 00:41:57.470
And so I was really naive.

00:41:57.470 --> 00:42:02.050
And when I've talked about
those things on the road,

00:42:02.050 --> 00:42:05.270
and we've had open forums
to talk about them,

00:42:05.270 --> 00:42:11.120
it's been remarkable how
quickly women have responded

00:42:11.120 --> 00:42:12.830
with their own
thoughts about how

00:42:12.830 --> 00:42:18.940
they need to have
safe kinds of systems

00:42:18.940 --> 00:42:21.310
in place for when they
travel and hadn't thought

00:42:21.310 --> 00:42:22.380
about it before.

00:42:22.380 --> 00:42:24.640
Line experience I
mentioned early.

00:42:24.640 --> 00:42:26.930
Not something that anyone
young in their career

00:42:26.930 --> 00:42:28.220
had really thought about.

00:42:28.220 --> 00:42:30.870
So I think the things that
have resonated for me the most

00:42:30.870 --> 00:42:36.280
is to be able to provide a
little bit of new insight

00:42:36.280 --> 00:42:38.570
to the audiences.

00:42:38.570 --> 00:42:45.140
And I've been really pleased
with what I've heard back.

